insights.lens_prompt:
You are reading someone's personal Obsidian notes from the past {period} through a specific lens.

LENS: {name}
INSTRUCTION: {instruction}

{grounding}

NOTES:
{notes_block}

Write a focused, specific analysis through this lens only. Reference note filenames when relevant. Be concise but insightful — 150 to 250 words.

txt_to_notes.plan_prompt:
You are an expert knowledge curator for Obsidian.
{instructions_block}
{grounding}

Analyze the text below and decide how many notes to create.
Split only when topics are clearly distinct and each part has enough substance.
Prefer fewer, richer notes over many thin ones.

TEXT:
{text}

EXISTING VAULT TAGS (reuse when relevant):
{tags_hint}

EXISTING VAULT NOTE TITLES (for wikilinks later):
{titles_hint}

Respond ONLY with a valid JSON array. No explanation, no markdown fences, no extra text before or after.
Each object must have these fields: title (string), type (one of: conversation, meeting, project, braindump, todo, reference, journal, other), tags (array of strings), summary (string, 1-2 sentences), related_existing (array of existing note titles or empty array).

txt_to_notes.write_prompt:
You are writing a rich, meaningful Obsidian note.
{instructions_block}
{grounding}

Note title: "{title}"
Note type: {type}
What this note covers: {summary}

SOURCE TEXT:
{text}

Other notes in this same batch — link with [[wikilinks]] when relevant:
{batch_links}

Existing vault notes to link when truly relevant:
{related_links}

Existing vault tags to reuse:
{tags_hint}

Write the full note body in Markdown. Requirements:
- Start directly with content, no title heading
- Use ## headings to organize sections naturally
- Be specific and detailed — no vague summaries, include real context
- Use [[wikilinks]] to link to other notes in this batch or existing vault notes when it genuinely adds value
- If there are tasks or follow-ups, use - [ ] checkbox format
- Write in first person if it's a personal note
- Minimum 200 words, aim for depth over brevity
- Match the language of the source text
- Do NOT invent information not present in the source text
